<font color="#FF0000">ANGER IS MUTUAL TO US BOTH</font><br>
<tt>Tue Aug 12 22:55:48 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Chet, you are always the peacemaker, much more than Jimmy &quot;I can build me some homes&quot; Carter. Ed and I have moved our &quot;discussion&quot; to a later thread, (111? the parking lot) and surprise, we have begun to talk. Fuckin' amazing &amp; good.<br><br>
People seem to think that &quot;war resistors&quot;, not peace protestors which is a term I am not in agreement with, have no anger over the outcome from Viet Nam. That is wrong thinking. Fuzzy Logic. I resisted a war, not war in general. There is a very big difference in that. I am not the typical Quaker or C.O. who says all war is wrong. I never said that. I just said the VN war was wrong, and gambled prison on the outcome of the dice. And I paid the civilian price for it.<br><br>
I feel ripped off over the way viet nam ended, just like many vets and Ed Ramon do. Ripped off, perhaps, for a different reason, but ripped off in the way it ended. Not with &quot;honor&quot;, not with &quot;reason&quot;, not with &quot;dignity&quot; but with Richard Nixon's cleaning up of LBJ's philosophy, and it looked like, acted like, smelled like, and looked like Texas politics at the end.  You bet I feel ripped off too. This was not honor, this was a &quot;deal&quot; in the vilest of terms, and a slap at both those who died, survived, and resisted.<br><br>
Surprise to all you vets, this is one war resistor, and I use that term intentionally, RESISTER, who does not like nor approve of how the war ended.  Ending the war was good, how it was done was a shame to those who sacraficed and died.  <br><br>
I for one, would take all the politicians, on both sides, and strip them to their underwear, and put them in a rice paddy with one knife per man. And then I would say, &quot;Go Boys&quot;, cause only half of you are coming out. Then I would repeat the performance, until we were finally down to 2 or 4 or 6. Then I would say, &quot;Hey you guys, you still think sending young boys (of someone else) to war is so great?&quot;.  I think you know the answer now, finally.<br><br>
Ed, and the former Cook (Hey Cook, where are you? Like calling for Car 54-Where are you?) and I have demonstrated that the two extremes can talk, can think, can share, and can feel.  And guess what. Some of the anger we both feel, 35 years later, is the same.  Ain't that somethin'? It is anger, but it does not have to be at each other. Anger at each other is just another way we were both manipulated by our leaders.<br><br>
doc
